AGI - A hundred years ago Giacomo Matteotti gave his last speech, what would cost him his life. The House from which it was pronounced will no longer be occupied by other deputies from today, the day when the House of Montecitorio recalled the sacrifice of socialist parliamentary, killed on June 10, 2024 by a fascist team led by Amerigo Dumini. Present the highest offices of the State, starting from the President of the Republic, Sergio Mattarella >che, welcomed by President Lorenzo Fontana, visited the exhibition set up in Transatlantic with the President of the Senate, Ignazio La Russo>, and the President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni>.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The ceremony began with the execution of Mameli's hymn and the hymn to joy. Also present are former presidents Gianfranco Fini and Luciano Violante, former premier Mario Monti. Among others, ministers Carlo Nordio and Andrea Abodi and the secretary of the Pd, Elly Schlein.
&nbsp;
"Today the House honors Matteotti, one of the fathers of our democracy victim to the fascist squadron," said Fontana opening the celebration. On his scranno "is e&nbsp; a plaque is placed" and "in perpetual memory of his sacrifice this will no longer be assigned to any MP", he scanned the President of the Chamber, "in that session" Matteotti "doing' the annulment in block of the election of majority deputies, denouncing the climate of intimidation and violence in which the political elections of 6 April were held. He also detailedly denounced the jugs and falsifications made by the fascists in the electoral seats of the whole country. His intervention, of which some significant steps will be read today, was continually interrupted by very lively noises and protests, as reported by the stenographic report of the session "&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Giacomo Matteotti's death "was not vain", Fontana said, "he had in particular the protection of the weakest classes, who wanted to emancipate economically and culturally. He believed that this emancipation should take place by means of democratic political struggle, in the framework of the principles of freedom and the rule of law. Opposing itself to any form of prevarication and political violence, it claimed that Parliament's prerogatives were the highest expression of modern democracy. Already in previous interventions Matteotti had challenged the fascist procedural irregularities and misfortune of the rules. The work at the House, as it emerges from the letters to the beloved wife Velia, impeded Matteotti to the extreme." And again: "He spent hours and hours in the Library preparing his interventions at the Chamber, always well documented and punctual," he recalled.&nbsp;
<h2>Melons: "Free and brave man killed for his ideas"</h2>
"The lesson of Matteotti, today more than ever, reminds us that our democracy is such if it is based on respect for the other, on confrontation, on freedom, not on violence, overwhelming, intolerance and hatred for the political opponent," said the President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni, "the &nbsp; 30 May 1924, Giacomo Matteotti spoke in the House last speech. In that speech, Matteotti defended political freedom, embodied in parliamentary representation and free elections."
&nbsp;
"Today we are here to commemorate a free and brave man killed by fascist squads for his ideas. Honoring his memory is fundamental to remind us every day at a distance of 100 years from that speech the value of freedom of speech and thought against those who would like to arrogate the right to establish what is allowed to say and think and what not," the premier concluded.
